The Command Line Interface (CLI) in Azure provides a powerful way to interact with Azure services using text-based commands instead of the graphical Azure Portal. Azure CLI is especially useful for automation, scripting, and managing resources efficiently.

Azure CLI can be used across platforms like Windows, Linux, and macOS. It allows users to create, update, delete, and monitor resources directly from the terminal.

For example, instead of manually creating a virtual machine via the portal, a DevOps engineer can use a single CLI command to deploy it. This is highly beneficial when deploying multiple environments like development, testing, and production.

A real-life use case includes CI/CD pipelines where infrastructure needs to be provisioned automatically. Azure CLI commands can be embedded in scripts to create resources during deployment.

Another example is managing large-scale cloud environments. Instead of navigating multiple dashboards, administrators can quickly retrieve information or modify configurations using CLI commands, saving time and reducing human error.
